at 27:15 with the extraordinary punch line =E2=80=9Cand now what=3F Now do =
=0Ayou make $20 million a day=3F The answer is yes you do.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[5=
] The shareholders don=E2=80=99t necessarily get much say: Wojcicki would a=
cquire =0Athe company via a merger, so shareholders wouldn=E2=80=99t get to=
 decide whether or not =0Ato sell her the shares; she=E2=80=99d buy them au=
tomatically. The merger requires =0Aapproval by the board and by shareholde=
r vote, but she controls 49% of the vote =0Aso the shareholder vote will ge=
t the result she wants. Often a special =0Acommittee will insist on a =E2=
=80=9Cmajority of the minority=E2=80=9D vote, where the merger =0Aalso has =
to be approved by a majority of the shares not held by Wojcicki; that =0Age=
ts better legal treatment but is not an absolute requirement.Wojcicki=E2=80=
=99s =0Aproposal =0A<https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1804591/000114=
036125006615/xslSCHEDULE_13D_X01/primary_doc.xml>=0A would be contingent on=
